                    <p><i>The Enraged</i> was a project that took place during the first half of 2013.  The concept of the game was to create a similar feel to classic JRPG games like <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shining_Force">Shining Force</a> & <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fire_Emblem">Fire Emblem</a>, but implement modern technology.</p>
                    <p>With an objective of collecting $12,000 in support over 30 days, <i>The Enraged</i> received a total of 144 pledges, totaling 6,376.  Although the game did not reach the initial request, the experience gained was worth the effort.</p>
                    <p>Leading the design, I worked hard to articulate the goal of <i>The Enraged</i>.  An important aspect involved balancing the music with the mood of the post-apocalyptic setting, while still maintaining <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TH_ePPdEKPA">a classic 16-bit era feel</a>.</p>
                    <p>In researching for our Kickstarter launch, public relations played an important part of advertising. I created a list of websites that might be interested in a game like ours.  Ultimately over twenty news and blog sites were determined that an interest existed for <i>The Enraged</i>.  Consequently, we had an overwhelming turnout: we were featured as Indie Game HQ's indie game of the month; spoken highly of by <a href="https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2013/04/14/kickstarter-katchup-april-14th-2013/">Rock, Paper, Shotgun</a>; featured in Super Pani Land, a youtube news blogger from Australia; and several other sites also featured tiny features on us.</p>
                    <p>Working on the Kickstarter also gave the experience and practice of working on design documents that were shared with the development team and our sample audience.  This helped guide the overall design and figure out our target audience.</p>
                    <p>Continuing communications with our fans being important, I made sure the financial backers were being properly informed. We issued a total of seven updates over the 30 day Kickstarter. In addition, another task was to address any questions or comments our fans may have had.  As a result, an important key factor was the ability to relate and reinforce the core components of our game to our audience.</p>
                    
